usa: The United States broke diplomatic relations with Cuba.<sup id="cite_ref-326" class="reference">[326]</sup>

President Eisenhower gave his farewell address which warned of the "military–industrial complex".<sup id="cite_ref-327" class="reference">[327]</sup><sup id="cite_ref-328" class="reference">[328]</sup>
The United States embargo against Cuba came into force.<sup id="cite_ref-329" class="reference">[329]</sup>
President Kennedy signed Executive Order 10924, establishing the Peace Corps.<sup id="cite_ref-330" class="reference">[330]</sup>
The Twenty-third Amendment to the United States Constitution, which granted electors to the District of Columbia, was ratified.<sup id="cite_ref-331" class="reference">[331]</sup>
Bay of Pigs Invasion: The failed U.S. led invasion and attempted coup d'état of Cuban Prime Minister Fidel Castro took place.[332][333]
The Freedom Rides began in Washington D.C. after the failure to enforce the Supreme Court's ruling in Boynton v. Virginia.[334][335]
Alan Shepard piloted the Freedom 7 capsule to become the first American in space.<sup id="cite_ref-336" class="reference">[336]</sup>
President Kennedy proposed the Apollo program, with the goal of "landing a man on the moon and returning him safely to the earth."<sup id="cite_ref-337" class="reference">[337]</sup>
Vietnam War: President Kennedy deployed an additional 400 U.S. military advisors (900 total) to South Vietnam; totaling 3,200 American troops by 1963, and more than 11,000 by mid-1964.[338][339][340]
